statement.p:
A =\left(
\begin{array}{cc}
 2 & 3 \\
 0 & -5 \\
\end{array}
\right) , B =\left(
\begin{array}{c}
 0 \\
 \frac{1}{2} \\
 15 \\
\end{array}
\right) , and D =\left(
\begin{array}{ccc}
 1 & 2 & 5 \\
 6 & -2 & 3 \\
 4 & 2 & 8 \\
\end{array}
\right)
are 2\times 2, 3\times 1, and 3\times 3 matrices, respectively.

subsection.p:
First we ask ourselves: Is the matrix A =\left(
\begin{array}{cc}
 1 & 2 \\
 3 & 4 \\
\end{array}
\right) equal to the matrix B =\left(
\begin{array}{cc}
 1 & 2 \\
 3 & 5 \\
\end{array}
\right)? No, they are not because the corresponding entries in the second row, second column of the two matrices are not equal.

Next, is
 A =\left(
\begin{array}{ccc}
 1 & 2 & 3 \\
 4 & 5 & 6 \\
\end{array}
\right) equal to B=\left(
\begin{array}{cc}
 1 & 2 \\
 4 & 5 \\
\end{array}
\right)? No, although the corresponding entries in the first two columns are identical, B doesn't have a third column to compare to that of A. We formalize these observations in the following definition.

The first two operations we introduce are very natural and are not likely cause much confusion. The first is matrix addition. It seems natural that if

A =\left(
\begin{array}{cc}
 1 & 0 \\
 2 & -1 \\
\end{array}
\right)
and 
B =\left(
\begin{array}{cc}
 3 & 4 \\
 -5 & 2 \\
\end{array}
\right) , then A + B =\left(
\begin{array}{cc}
 1+3 & 0+4 \\
 2-5 & -1+2 \\
\end{array}
\right)=\left(
\begin{array}{cc}
 4 & 4 \\
 -3 & 1 \\
\end{array}
\right).

However, if A=\left(
\begin{array}{ccc}
 1 & 2 & 3 \\
 0 & 1 & 2 \\
\end{array}
\right) and B = \left(
\begin{array}{cc}
 3 & 0 \\
 2 & 8 \\
\end{array}
\right), is there a natural way to add them to give us A+B? No, the orders of the two matrices must be identical.

statement.p:
 If c = 3 and if A =\left(
\begin{array}{cc}
 1 & -2 \\
 3 & 5 \\
\end{array}
\right) and we wish to find c A, it seems natural to multiply each entry of A by 3 so that 3 A =\left(
\begin{array}{cc}
 3 & -6 \\
 9 & 15 \\
\end{array}
\right), and this is precisely the way scalar multiplication is defined.

Let A be an m\times n matrix and let B be an n\times p matrix. The product of A and B, denoted
by AB, is an m\times p matrix whose ith row jth column entry is
\begin{split}
(A B)_{ij}&= a_{i 1}b_{1 j}+a_{i 2}b_{2 j}+ \cdots +a_{i n}b_{n j}\\
&= \sum_{k=1}^n a_{i k} b_{k j}
\end{split}

for 1\leq i\leq m and 1\leq j\leq p.

example.p:
  Let A =\left(
\begin{array}{cc}
 1 & 0 \\
 3 & 2 \\
 -5 & 1 \\
\end{array}
\right), a 3\times 2 matrix, and let B =\left(
\begin{array}{c}
 6 \\
 1 \\
\end{array}
\right), a 2\times 1 matrix. Then A B is a 3 \times  1 matrix:
A B = \left(
\begin{array}{cc}
 1 & 0 \\
 3 & 2 \\
 -5 & 1 \\
\end{array}
\right) \left(
\begin{array}{c}
 6 \\
 1 \\
\end{array}
\right) = \left(
\begin{array}{c}
 1\cdot 6+0\cdot 1 \\
 3 \cdot 6 + 2\cdot 1 \\
 -5 \cdot 6 + 1\cdot 1 \\
\end{array}
\right) = \left(
\begin{array}{c}
 6 \\
 20 \\
 -29 \\
\end{array}
\right)

statement.p:
Let A =\left(
\begin{array}{cc}
 -1 & 0 \\
 0 & 3 \\
\end{array}
\right) and B =\left(
\begin{array}{cc}
 3 & 10 \\
 2 & 1 \\
\end{array}
\right) . Then

A B =\left(
\begin{array}{cc}
 -1\cdot 3 + 0\cdot 2 & -1\cdot 10+0\cdot 1 \\
 0\cdot 3+3\cdot 2 & 0\cdot 10+3\cdot 1 \\
\end{array}
\right)= \left(
\begin{array}{cc}
 -3 & -10 \\
 6 & 3 \\
\end{array}
\right)

Note: B A =\left(
\begin{array}{cc}
 -3 & 30 \\
 -	2 & 3 \\
\end{array}
\right) \neq A B.   The columns of B are multiplied by -1 and 3 when the order is switched.

 Let A = \left(
\begin{array}{ccc}
 1 & 0 & 2 \\
 2 & -1 & 5 \\
 3 & 2 & 1 \\
\end{array}
\right) , B =\left(
\begin{array}{ccc}
 0 & 2 & 3 \\
 1 & 1 & 2 \\
 -1 & 3 & -2 \\
\end{array}
\right) , and C=\left(
\begin{array}{cccc}
 2 & 1 & 2 & 3 \\
 4 & 0 & 1 & 1 \\
 3 & -1 & 4 & 1 \\
\end{array}
\right)
Compute, if possible;

 Let A =\left(
\begin{array}{cc}
 2 & 0 \\
 0 & 3 \\
\end{array}
\right) . Find a matrix B such that A B = I and B A = I, where I = \left(
\begin{array}{cc}
 1 & 0 \\
 0 & 1 \\
\end{array}
\right).

 Find A I and B I where I is as in Exercise 3, where
A = \left(
\begin{array}{cc}
 1 & 8 \\
 9 & 5 \\
\end{array}
\right) and B = \left(
\begin{array}{cc}
 -2 & 3 \\
 5 & -7 \\
\end{array}
\right). 
 What do you notice?

li.p:
If A =\left(
\begin{array}{cc}
 2 & 1 \\
 1 & -1 \\
\end{array}
\right), X =\left(
\begin{array}{c}
 x_1 \\
 x_2 \\
\end{array}
\right)\textrm{, and }B =\left(
\begin{array}{c}
 3 \\
 1 \\
\end{array}
\right), show that A X =B is a way of expressing the system  
    \begin{array}{c}2x_1 + x_2 = 3\\ x_1 - x_2= 1\\
    \end{array}  using matrices.

Ax=\left(
\begin{array}{c}
 2x_1+1x_2 \\
 1x_1-1x_2 \\
\end{array}
\right) equals \left(
\begin{array}{c}
 3 \\
 1 \\
\end{array}
\right) if and only if both of the equalities 
     2x_1+x_2=3 \textrm{ and } x_1-x_2=1 are true.
